ormally distributed</em></p></div>
          </div>
        </div></div><div class=3D"default-content-wrapper"><h2 id=3D"summar=
y-of-features">Summary of features</h2><p>The normal distribution has the f=
ollowing features:</p><ol>
          <li>It is completely defined by the mean and <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.jmp.com/en/statistics-knowledge-portal/measures-of-central-tendency-and-=
variability/standard-deviation" title=3D"standard deviation">standard devia=
tion</a>.</li>
          <li>The <a href=3D"https://www.jmp.com/en/statistics-knowledge-po=
rtal/measures-of-central-tendency-and-variability/mean-median-and-mode" tit=
le=3D"mean, median and mode">mean, median and mode</a> are all identical.</=
li>
          <li>It is symmetrical.</li>
          <li>It is bell-shaped.</li>
        </ol><p>Each feature is significant and tells you something about y=
our data. Let's take a closer look:</p><h3 id=3D"completely-defined-by-mean=
-and-standard-deviation"><strong>1. Completely defined by mean and standard=
 deviation</strong></h3><p>We need only two values =E2=80=93 the mean and t=
he standard deviation =E2=80=93 to draw a picture of a specific normal dist=
ribution. (To further explore the relationship between the mean and the sta=
ndard deviation for normally distributed data, read about the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.jmp.com/en/statistics-knowledge-portal/measures-of-central-tenden=
cy-and-variability/empirical-rule" title=3D"empirical rule">empirical rule<=
/a>.)</p><p>The mean and standard deviation are referred to as the <em>para=
meters</em> of the normal distribution. All distributions have parameters, =
and some have more than two. In any situation, the parameters will define a=
 specific distribution.</p><p>Let's look at some examples of normal distrib=
ution curves.</p><p>Figure 2 shows two normal distributions, each with the =
same mean of 30. The thinner, taller distribution shown in blue has a stand=
ard deviation of 5. The wider, shorter distribution shown in orange has a s=
tandard deviation of 10.</p><p>
