            <div><p><em>Figure 5: True normal distribution in which mean, m=
edian, and mode are the same</em></p></div>
          </div>
        </div></div><div class=3D"default-content-wrapper"><h3 id=3D"symmet=
rical"><strong>3. Symmetrical</strong></h3><p>The normal distribution is sy=
mmetrical. If you think about folding the graph in half at the mean, each s=
ide will be the same.</p><h3 id=3D"bell-shaped"><strong>4. Bell-shaped</str=
ong></h3><p>The normal distribution is bell-shaped with one central =E2=80=
=9Chump,=E2=80=9D which can be seen in the examples above.</p><p>Figure 6 s=
hows a distribution that is non-normal. It has two humps instead of one. A =
distribution with two humps could indicate that there are different groups =
that are mixed up in the data. For example, heart rates are usually normall=
y distributed. But suppose, unknown to you, the data has the resting heart =
rate for two groups: athletes and inactive people. You might get a bimodal =
distribution like the one below.</p><p>
